			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: What do bards want?<a name="25726"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 5 04 12:57 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>If you just rolled your shaman, then I think the answer is damage and healing.  At low levels, neither shaman slow nor bard slow really means much.  The small percentages of slow simply don't really have a material impact on the fights.  Probably you will both tank to some degree, but you will be in charge of heals.
<br />

<br />
At higher levels, both classes specialties come into play more significantly.  I frequently duo with a shaman, and what she does is:
<br />

<br />
1.  Buff us both (obvious)
<br />

<br />
2.  Slows on pulls -- we coordinate me pulling with a resist debuff so she can land slows easily.
<br />

<br />
3.  Roots and dots adds, so we move through more mobs faster.
<br />

<br />
4.  Heals both of us.
<br />

<br />
5.  Adds DPS with dots and dog pet.
<br />

<br />

<br />
That's assuming a duo.  In a group, roles vary.  Sometimes she's the main healer, in which case I try to use my slow to buy her time to get control of the situation.  Other times, she's DPS with the fast poison DOTs.  Other times, she seems to mainly be melee support, casting SLTW &amp; FA over and over again.
<br />

<br />
One thing you should do is coordinate with your bard what dots and debuffs you will be casting.  Depending on group makeup, I often work one of our DOT chants into my normal mix.  Each chant does damage over time but also debuffs a particular resist.  So keep communication open about what's getting resisted most.  If she's having trouble landing Bane of Nife, I work in Chant of Poison.  If she's having trouble landing new Bane, I work in the magic resist debuff DOT.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"></span></td>
